SIMPLE: signal
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Signal
<hw>Sig"nal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. LL.
<ets>signale</ets>, fr. L. <ets>signum</ets>. See <er>Sign</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A sign made for the purpose of
giving notice to a person of some occurrence, command, or danger; also,
a sign, event, or watchword, which has been agreed upon as the occasion
of concerted action.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All obeyed⟦br⟧
The wonted <qex>signal</qex> and superior voice⟦br⟧
Of this great potentate.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A token; an indication; a foreshadowing; a sign;
anything taken as evidence of some process.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>The weary sun . . . ⟦br⟧
Gives <qex>signal</qex> of a goodly day to-morrow.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There was not the least <qex>signal</qex> of the calamity to be
seen.</q> <rj><qau>De Foc.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <fld>(Electronics)</fld> <def>A
measurable electrical quantity, such as voltage or current, that conveys
information by varying in magnitude over time; <as>as, the
<ex>signals</ex> from the strongest commercial radio stations can be
received over hundreds of miles</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Signal to noise</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Signal to noise ratio</ent>⟦br⟧
<mhw>

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Signal
<hw>Sig"nal</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From <ets>signal</ets>, n.: cf. F.
<ets>signal⟦eacute⟧</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Noticeable;
distinguished from what is ordinary; eminent; remarkable; memorable;
<as>as, a <ex>signal</ex> exploit; a <ex>signal</ex> service; a
<ex>signal</ex> act of benevolence</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As <qex>signal</qex> now in low, dejected state⟦br⟧
As erst in highest, behold him where he lies.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to signals, or the use of signals
in conveying information; <as>as, a <ex>signal</ex> flag or
officer</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>The signal service</b></col>, <cd>a bureau of the
government (in the United States connected with the War Department)
organized to collect from the whole country simultaneous raports of
local meteorological conditions, upon comparison of which at the central
office, predictions concerning the weather are telegraphed to various
sections, where they are made known by signals publicly displayed.</cd>
-- <col><b>Signal station</b></col>, <cd>the place where a signal is
displayed; specifically, an observation office of the signal
service.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Eminent; remarkable; memorable; extraordinary;
notable; conspicuous.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Signal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Signal
<hw>Sig"nal</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Signaled</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr> ⟦or⟧ <conjf>Signalled</conjf>;
<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Signaling</conjf> or
<conjf>Signalling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To communicate by
signals; <as>as, to <ex>signal</ex> orders</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To notify by a signals; to make a signal or signals
to; <as>as, to <ex>signal</ex> a fleet to anchor</as>.</def> <rj><au>M.
Arnold.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Signalist</ent>⟦br⟧
